---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Job from "../components/Job.astro";
---

<Layout
        title="My Portfolio - Experience"
        description="The experience page for my portfolio"
>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6 text-primary">Professional Experience</h1>

    <div class="space-y-6 mb-10">
        <Job
                title="Frontend Developer"
                company="Company A"
                dates="Jan 2022 – Present"
                location="Remote"
        >
            <li>Start each bullet point with a strong action verb (e.g., "Built," "Led," "Improved").</li>
            <li>Focus on results and impact, not just tasks. Ask yourself: *What changed because of your work?*</li>
            <li>Include numbers where possible such as percentages, dollars, time saved, etc.</li>
            <li>Keep it concise and easy to scan. Imagine someone skimming your resume in 5 seconds.</li>
        </Job>

        <Job
                title="UI/UX Designer"
                company="Company B"
                dates="Jun 2020 – Dec 2021"
                location="New York, NY"
        >
            The default design of this component doesn’t clearly indicate it’s clickable. This is intentional. Follow
            the tips below to follow best design practices and indicate to the user it's clickable.

            <li>
                Add the class <code class="bg-base-300 px-1 rounded">collapse-arrow</code> to the same
                <code class="bg-base-300 px-1 rounded">&lt;div class="collapse"&gt;</code> to include an arrow
                indicator.
            </li>
            <li>
                Make it visually interactive: change
                <code class="bg-base-300 px-1 rounded">bg-base-200</code> to
                <code class="bg-base-300 px-1 rounded">bg-base-300</code> on hover.
            </li>
            <li>
                If you’re curious how to do that in Tailwind, search for:
                <em>"how to change the state of a component in Tailwind when you're hovering over it"</em>
                (hint: look into <code>hover:</code>, <code>group</code>, and <code>peer</code> utilities).
            </li>
            <li>There's also an example of it in the <code>Job.astro</code> component, so definitely look there for
                inspiration.
            </li>
        </Job>

        <Job
                title="Software Engineering Intern"
                company="Company C"
                dates="Summer 2019"
                location="San Francisco, CA"
        >
            <li>Optimized React app with dynamic imports and code splitting, reducing load time by 35%.</li>
            <li>Built a shared component library in TypeScript, cutting dev time for new features by 20%.</li>
            <li>Improved end-to-end test coverage with Cypress, lowering QA-reported bugs by 50%.</li>
        </Job>
    </div>


    <div class="divider"/>

    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold my-6 text-primary">Skills</h1>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside grid grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 text-lg gap-y-2 text-base-content/80">
        <li>C#</li>
        <li>Razor Pages</li>
        <li>MySQL</li>
        <li>SQLite</li>
        <li>HTML</li>
        <li>CSS</li>
        <li>JavaScript</li>
        <li>Astro</li>
        <li>Svelte</li>
        <li>Bootstrap</li>
        <li>TailwindCSS</li>
        <li>DaisyUI</li>
        <li>GitHub</li>
        <li>Agile</li>
        <li>SCRUM</li>
        <li>Lean</li>
    </ul>
</Layout>
